Can&#x27;t remember exactly how I did it. However I found something similar that waits for a command to complete sed instead of grep. sed exists after the first match:<p><pre><code>    send_to_mc &quot;/wb SomeWorld trim 100 15 C-m&quot;
    sleep 1
    send_to_mc &quot;/wb trim confirm&quot;
    tail -n 0 -F &quot;logs/latest.log&quot; | sed &quot;/trimmed so far (100.0% done)/q&quot;
    send_to_mc &quot;/broadcast Chunk deletion done&quot;

</code></pre>
<i>send_to_mc</i> is simply sending <i>$1</i> + <i>return</i> to tmux:<p><pre><code>    tmux send -t &quot;$tmux_session&quot; &quot;$1&quot; C-m
</code></pre>
<i>/wb</i> is a command from the WorldBorder [0] command that is (in this case) used to delete all chunks (which were generated for some reason) beyond the border.<p>using <i>while read line</i> is probably the best option if you want to continuously check the logs
You could also use awk isntead of grep:<p><pre><code>    awk &quot;/pattern/{print $0}&quot;

</code></pre>
